    "title": "Column Anchorage",
    "plainText": "COLUMN ANCHORAGE HAZARD MODULE\n\nAnchor rods, base plates, leveling, plumbing, and release conditions for steel columns\n\nThis hazard element addresses the first structural interface between the steel frame and the supporting concrete or masonry. It is intended for planning, training, and pre-task review as a hazard-specific control document.\n\n1. Risks & Hazards\n\n1.1 Main hazard condition  The main exposure in this element is misaligned bases, damaged or modified anchor rods, missing hardware, poor leveling, premature loading, and collapse from unsafe base conditions. The hazard often develops quickly because steel erection changes the work surface, the load path, and the location of workers throughout the shift.\n\n1.2 Why this hazard escalates  This exposure becomes more severe when the crew is rushed, when the sequence changes, or when the site assumes the work is routine even though the controlling conditions have changed since the last pick or connection step.\n\n2. Work Planning Steps (Pre-Task & Pre-Construction)\n\n2.1 Planning focus  The pre-task plan should address written concrete-strength notice, anchor-rod status, base elevations, shim or leveling methods, and the release condition for each column line. The plan should also identify who is responsible for stop-work decisions if conditions do not match the intended method.\n\n2.2 Daily review  The daily review should confirm weather, manpower, task order, adjacent-trade coordination, restricted areas, and whether any condition from the prior shift remains unresolved before this hazard is reintroduced.\n\n3. Structural Stability Requirements\n\n3.1 Stability link  The structural stability issue tied to this hazard is that columns require the proper anchorage and temporary restraint before the next steel is introduced. Stability and hazard control should therefore be reviewed together rather than as separate topics.\n\n3.2 Temporary conditions  Temporary conditions should be reviewed as real structural or exposure conditions, not as acceptable gaps that will be fixed later when time allows.\n\n4. Connecting & Decking Requirements\n\n4.1 Connection or deck interaction  This hazard is strongly affected by base accuracy affects later beam, joist, and brace fit-up higher in the frame. The crew should know exactly when the area changes from an active erection zone to a released work zone.\n\n4.2 Access restrictions  Access should stay limited to the workers actually engaged in the operation until the hazard controls for that area are complete and communicated.\n\n5. Training Requirements\n\n5.1 Hazard recognition  Employees should be trained to recognize when this hazard is present, when it has become worse because of changing conditions, and when the correct response is to stop and re-plan instead of pushing through.\n\n5.2 Role-specific training  Role-specific training should cover the employeeâ€™s exact responsibility, the limits of the method being used, and the communication steps required when the hazard cannot be controlled as planned.\n\n6. Certification Requirements\n\n6.1 Qualified or competent oversight  Competent or qualified oversight should be identified before work begins so inspection responsibility, lift authority, and stop-work authority are not left unclear.\n\n6.2 Record expectations  Where the project or employer uses written pre-task plans, special lift records, training records, or technical approvals, those records should support this hazard element and not conflict with it.\n\n7. Required Equipment\n\n7.1 Core equipment  Typical equipment for controlling this hazard includes anchor-bolt plans, levels, measuring tools, shim packs, leveling nuts where used, spud wrenches, drift pins, erection bolts, radios, and lifting equipment. Equipment should be selected and staged before the hazard zone is opened.\n\n7.2 PPE and support items  Required PPE and support items should be suitable for the task without creating a second problem such as poor mobility, snagging, poor communication, or blocked access.\n\n8. Required Permits (If Applicable)\n\n8.1 Typical permit triggers  Projects may require approval for anchor-rod repair, base modification, engineered shimming changes, or deviation from approved anchor-bolt information. Even when no separate permit is used, the pre-task plan should still document the controlling assumptions.\n\n8.2 Documentation path  Any condition that changes the planned method should be routed through the projectâ€™s approval or technical path rather than solved informally in the field.\n\n9. Trades Most Affected\n\n9.1 Primary affected parties  The trades most directly affected are raising crews, connection crews, survey or layout personnel, crane operators, supervisors, concrete crews, and controlling-contractor representatives. These parties should be addressed in the coordination plan for the work zone.\n\n9.2 Shared responsibility  Other site users may also be affected if they enter, work below, or route materials through the area while the hazard remains active.\n\n10. Additional Related Information\n\n10.1 Practical use  This document works best when it is reviewed before the task starts and then used again whenever the crew changes sequence, location, or equipment.\n\n10.2 End-of-shift review  At the end of the shift, the area should be reviewed for unresolved controls, damaged equipment, or restricted zones that need to remain in effect for the next crew.\n\nREFERENCE LANGUAGE AND OSHA SOURCE POINTS\n\nThe inline markers below correspond to the requirement language referenced in the body of this document.\n\nR1. Steel erection begins only after written notification that the concrete in footings, piers, walls, or masonry piers or walls has attained the strength to support erection loads. OSHA 1926.752(a)(1).\n\nR2. The controlling contractor must provide the steel erector written notification of repairs, replacements, or field modifications to anchor rods before column erection. OSHA 1926.752(a)(2) and 1926.755(b).\n\nR3. The controlling contractor must ensure adequate access roads, site conditions, and storage areas for safe steel erection. OSHA 1926.752(c).\n\nR5. A competent person must perform a pre-shift visual inspection of cranes used in steel erection, and a qualified rigger must inspect rigging prior to each shift. OSHA 1926.753(c).\n\nR6. Structural stability must be maintained at all times during the erection process. OSHA 1926.754(a).\n\nR7. Columns must be anchored by a minimum of four anchor rods. OSHA 1926.755(a)(1).\n\nR8. Solid web structural members must be secured with at least two bolts per connection before release from the hoisting line. OSHA 1926.756(a)(1).\n\nR12. Falling object protection is required where tools, equipment, or materials could strike employees below. OSHA 1926.759.\n\nR14. Employers must initiate and maintain accident prevention programs and provide frequent and regular inspections by competent persons. OSHA 1926.20(b)(1)-(2).\n\nR15. The employer shall instruct each employee in the recognition and avoidance of unsafe conditions and the regulations applicable to the work environment. OSHA 1926.21(b)(2).\n\nR17. The employer is responsible for requiring appropriate personal protective equipment wherever employees are exposed to hazardous conditions. OSHA 1926.28(a).",
